  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThe article debunks the “just add more engineers” shortcut, arguing that team size drives a quadratic rise in communication paths (n · (n‑1)/2) and coordination overhead, which quickly outweighs any nominal gain in capacity. It cites research from Microsoft, *Accelerate*, and Brooks’ Law to show that larger, less autonomous teams are slower, lower‑quality, and take 3‑6 months before new senior hires become productive, further eroding deadline gains. The piece uses concrete metaphors—“two‑pizza teams,” “baby‑making analogy,” and O(n²) growth—to frame its analysis, positioning itself as a pragmatic, data‑driven rant aimed at engineering managers, VPs, and technical leads who wrestle with staffing decisions.",
